[[File:Hudson_anti_suffrage.png|alt=Anti-suffrage leaders, Mrs. George Phillips, Mrs. K.B. Lapham, Miss Burham, Mrs. Evertt P. Wheeler and Mrs. John A. Church at an anti-suffrage event on the Hudson River, May 30, 1913.|thumb|300x300px|Anti-suffrage leaders, Mrs. George Phillips, Mrs. K.B. Lapham, Miss Burham, Mrs. Evertt P. Wheeler and Mrs. John A. Church at an anti-suffrage event on the Hudson River, May 30, 1913.]]
'''Anti-suffragism''' was a political movement composed of both men and women that began in the late 19th century in order to campaign against [[women's suffrage]] in countries such as [[Australia]], [[Canada]], [[Ireland]], the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]]. Anti-suffragism was a largely [[Conservatism|conservative]] movement that sought to keep the [[status quo]] for women and which opposed the idea giving women equal suffrage rights. It was closely associated with "domestic feminism," the belief that women had the right to complete freedom within the home. In the United States, these activists were often referred to as "remonstrants" or "antis."

== Background ==
The anti-suffrage movement was a [[countermovement]] opposing the social movement of [[women's suffrage]] in various countries.{{Sfn|Burt|1998|p=69}} It could also be considered a [[Public sphere|counterpublic]] that espoused a [[Conservatism|Conservative]] defense of the [[status quo]] for women and men in society.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=285}} As a countermovement, the anti-suffrage movement didn't gain traction or start to organize until the women's suffrage began to challenge the current [[social order]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a9lFXY0kkEwC&lpg=PA175&ots=6cdHKX58Pg&dq=anti-suffragist%20countermovement&pg=PA175#v=onepage&q=anti-suffragist%20countermovement&f=false|title=Women's Movements in the United States: Woman Suffrage, Equal Rights, and Beyond|last=Buechler|first=Steven M.|date=1990|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=|isbn=9780813515595|location=|pages=175|language=en}}</ref>

Countries in the [[Western world|Western World]] began to explore giving women the equal right to vote around the mid 1800s.<ref name=":2" /> Areas with the most visible women's suffrage movements were [[Great Britain]] and in the [[United States]], although women's suffrage movements took place in many Western countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/woman-suffrage|title=Woman suffrage|last=|first=|date=|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514012354/https://www.britannica.com/topic/woman-suffrage|archive-date=14 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> Anti-suffrage activities began to emerge in many countries as women publicly advocated for suffrage.{{Sfn|Burt|1998|p=70}}

== Australia ==
Anti suffrage movements were present in [[Australia]] through the 1880s and 1890s.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0453b.htm|title=Suffragists|last=Grimshaw|first=Patricia|date=|website=The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410015728/http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0453b.htm|archive-date=10 April 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-20}}</ref> Anti-suffrage organisations in Australia were "closely associated with the [[Conservative Party of Australia|Conservative Party]], manufacturing interests and anti-[[Socialism|socialist]] forces."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womensuffrage.org/?p=576|title=The Opponents of Woman Suffrage|last=Strong-Boag|first=Veronica|date=1 February 2012|website=Women Suffrage and Beyond|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429033348/http://womensuffrage.org/?p=576|archive-date=29 April 2017|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-20}}</ref> The Australian media took part in the anti-suffrage movement, and depicted women as being "weak and unintelligent," emotional and too involved in domestic and trivial matters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/blogs/on-this-day/2011/12/on-this-day-women-get-the-federal-vote|title=On this day: women get the federal vote|last=Verdouw|first=Emily|date=15 December 2011|work=Australian Geographic|access-date=2018-05-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515143647/http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/blogs/on-this-day/2011/12/on-this-day-women-get-the-federal-vote|archive-date=15 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>

== Canada ==
[[Canadians|Canadian]] men and women both became involved in debating the women's suffrage movement in the late 1800s.{{Sfn|Risk|2012|p=384}} Women's suffrage was debated in the Legislative Assembly in [[New Brunswick]] starting in 1885, and anti-suffrage "testimonies" began to appear in the newspapers around that time.{{Sfn|Risk|2012|p=389}}

==Great Britain==
[[File:Anti-suffrage postcard- While in the act of voting.jpg|thumb|Anti-suffrage postcard- "While in the act of voting"]]
[[File:Anti-suffrage postcard- For a Suffragette the Ducking-Stool.jpg|thumb|Anti-suffrage postcard- For a Suffragette the Ducking-Stool.jpg]]
Organized campaigns against women's suffrage began in earnest in 1905, around the same time that [[suffragette]]s were turning to [[militant]] tactics.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=7}} In general, most ordinary women had prioritized domestic and family life over paid employment and political activism when it came to the issue of suffrage.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|pp=308-309}} Most historical evidence shows that ordinary women did not have much interest in the right to vote before the first World War and also after suffrage had been granted to women.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|p=311 "The range of evidence gathered from modern historians seems to confirm the view that the 'ordinary woman' had little interest in the vote before the war, and only limited interest once it had been finally placed in her hand."}}   

The [[Women's National Anti-Suffrage League]] was established in London on 21 July 1908. Its aims were to oppose women being granted the vote in British parliamentary elections, although it did support their having votes in local government elections. It was founded at a time when there was a resurgence of support for the women's suffrage movement.

The Women's National Anti-Suffrage League, publisher of the ''Anti-Suffrage Review'', submitted a petition to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] in 1907 with 87,500 names, but it was rejected by the Petitions Committee of Parliament as "informal".<ref>Elizabeth Robins, [http://www.jsu.edu/depart/english/robins/waysta/way02tpb.htm Way Stations (1913)], p. 37</ref> The ''Anti-Suffrage Review'' also used [[shame]] as a tool to fight against the suffrage movement.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=6}}

An Anti-suffrage correspondence had taken place in the pages of ''[[The Times]]'' through 1906–1907, with further calls for leadership of the anti-suffrage movement being placed in ''[[The Spectator]]'' in February 1908. Possibly as early as 1907, a letter was circulated to announce the creation of a National Women's Anti-Suffrage Association and inviting recipients to become a member of the Central Organising Committee or a member. It was issued under the names of thirty peeresses who would become prominent anti-suffragists, as well as a number of peers and MPs. However, the first meeting of the Women's National Anti-Suffrage League only took place the following year on 21 July, at the Westminster Palace Hotel with [[Victor Child Villiers, 7th Earl of Jersey#Family|Lady Jersey]] in the Chair. Seventeen persons were nominated to the central committee at this meeting, including [[Mrs Humphrey Ward]] in the chair of the Literary Committee and [[Gertrude Bell]] as secretary. Other members were Mrs Frederic Harrison, Miss Lonsdale, [[Violet Markham]] and [[Hilaire Belloc]] MP. Beatrice Chamberlain served as the editor of the ''Anti-Suffrage Review''.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=8}}

The League's aims were to oppose women being granted the parliamentary franchise, though it did support their having votes in local and municipal elections. It published the ''Anti-Suffrage Review'' from December 1908 until 1918. It gathered 337,018 signatures on an anti-suffrage petition and founded the first local branch in Hawkenhurst in Kent. The first London branch was established in South Kensington under the auspices of Mary, Countess of Ilchester. Soon after, in May 1910, a Scottish branch was organised into the Scottish National Anti-Suffrage League by the Duchess of Montrose. By December of that year, there were 26 branches or sub-branches in the country, a total which grew to 82 by April 1909, and 104 in July 1910. It was announced that 2000 subscriptions had been received by December, 1908, rising to 9000 in July, 1909.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}

In 1910, the group amalgamated with the [[Men's League for Opposing Woman Suffrage]]<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/votes-for-women/articles/the-anti-suffrage-movement|title=The Anti-Suffrage Movement|last=Bush|first=Julia|date=5 March 2018|website=The British Library|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326122211/https://www.bl.uk/votes-for-women/articles/the-anti-suffrage-movement|archive-date=26 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> to form the [[National League for Opposing Women's Suffrage]]{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=7}} with [[Evelyn Baring, 1st Earl of Cromer|Lord Cromer]] as president and Lady Jersey as Vice-President. The merger was in effect a takeover, as the president of the former organisation, Lord Cromer, becoming president of the new one.<ref>Roger Owen, ''Lord Cromer: Victorian Imperialist, Edwardian Proconsul'', Oxford University Press (2004), page 376. {{ISBN|0-19-927966-7}}</ref> In 1912 [[Lord Curzon]] and [[Lord Weardale]] became joint presidents. By 1914, there were around 15,000 members.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=9}} The organisation continued its activities and the publication of the ''Anti-Suffrage Review'' until 1918 when both came to an end as women's suffrage was granted.<ref name=":6" />

=== Reasons for suffrage opposition ===
The opposition to the right for women to vote was a multifaceted phenomenon in which women themselves played a major part.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|p=2 "Women's roles in the British anti-suffrage movement were important, and in some ways distinctive. Women provided a good deal of the initiative and most of the hard work behind the organized opposition, as well as the majority of its declared supporters."}} One of the reasons for opposition from women was that they believed that women were already equal without needing to be able to vote, although women were expected to be "equal" in different spheres from men.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=10}} Anti-suffragists were also appalled by the tactics of Suffragettes, who they believed "had attacked the very essence of English womanhood."{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=11}} 

Many female maternal reformers, who sought to protect women's defined spheres of motherhood, education, philanthropy, and civil service; felt that women were the better sex for preserving British society through social service to their communities rather than by meddling with politics.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|p=23}} Women considered themselves as less able to participate in politics and that to do so was women just imitating men, instead of being "real women."{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=10}} Some feared that the right to vote would introduce uninformed women in making decisions on important political matters. Since Britain was in the process of colonizing other regions around the globe, some viewed the right to vote as a threat to their imperial power as it would make the British look weak by other nations who were male oriented still.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|pp=109-112}} Some suffragist female groups developed militant and violent tactics which tarnished the image of women as innocent people that the anti-suffragists had been striving to preserve. Anti-suffragists used theses acts as a reasons to show that women were mentally unable to handle political matters and that both genders had different strengths.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|pp=227-231}}     

Women writers promoted anti-suffragism through their wide readerships by raising questions of what ideal women were to be like.{{Sfn|Bush|2007|p=23}}</ref>

== Ireland ==
Women's suffrage movements had been going on in [[Ireland]] since the 1870s.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=12}} However, as Suffragettes in Ireland became more militant, more organized anti-suffrage campaigns emerged.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=12-13}} An Irish branch of the [[Women's National Anti-Suffrage League]] was started in 1909 in [[Dublin]].<ref name=":9">{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/heritage/century/century-women-and-the-vote/opponents-of-the-cause-1.553535|title=Opponents of the Cause|last=Lane|first=Leeann|date=17 October 2012|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-05-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421032702/https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/heritage/century/century-women-and-the-vote/opponents-of-the-cause-1.553535|archive-date=21 April 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> This branch of the League also opposed suffrage in Britain as well.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=13}}

=== Reasons for suffrage opposition ===
Irish opposition to the women's vote was both religious and cultural. Both [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and [[Protestantism|Protestant]] churches in Ireland wanted women's influence to remain domestic in nature.<ref name=":9" /> Women were closely associated with their husbands for legal and political purposes and it was argued that husband's votes were sufficient to allow a woman's political expression.<ref name=":9" />

[[Irish nationalism]] also played a role in anti-suffrage movements.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=14}} Because of the nationalistic movements going on in Ireland, both men and women nationalists opposed giving women the vote because they were prioritizing [[Irish Home Rule movement|Irish Home Rule]].{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=14}} A nationalist paper, ''[[Bean na hÉireann]],'' which was published by the [[Inghinidhe na hÉireann|Inghinidhe na hÉirann]] (Daughters of Ireland), took a very anti-suffrage stance.{{Sfn|Crozier-De Rosa|2014|p=17-18}}

==United States==
While men were involved in the anti-suffrage movement in the [[United States]], most anti-suffrage groups were led and supported by women.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=36}} While these groups openly stated that they wanted [[politics]] to be left to men, it was more often women addressing political bodies with anti-suffrage arguments.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=36}} During the fight to pass the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|nineteenth amendment]], women increasingly took on a leading role in the anti-suffrage movement.{{Sfn|Dodd|2013|p=713}}

[[Helen Kendrick Johnson|Helen Kendrick Johnson's]] ''Woman and the Republic'' (1897) was a lauded anti-suffrage book that described the reasons for opposing women's right to vote.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=36}} Other books, such as [[Molly Elliot Seawell|Molly Elliot Seawell's]] ''The Ladies' Battle'' (1911), [[Ida Tarbell|Ida Tarbell's]] ''The Business of Being a Woman'' (1912), [[Grace Duffield Goodwin|Grace Duffield Goodwin's]] ''Anti-Suffrage: Ten Good Reasons'' (1915) and [[Annie Riley Hale|Annie Riley Hale's]] ''The Eden Sphinx'' (1916) were similarly well-received by the media and used as a "coherent rationale for opposing women's enfranchisement."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=36}}

Anti-suffrage [[drama]]s were also published between the mid 1800s and up to the 1920s.{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=302}} The first playwright to create anti-suffrage plays was [[William Bentley Fowle]], who wrote the one-act play for amateurs, ''Women's Rights'', published in 1856.{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=302}} Later plays were adapted for the professional stage, such as ''The Rights of Man'' (1857) by Oliver S. Leland and ''Election Day'' (1880) by [[Frank Dumont]].{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=302}} [[Nellie Locke]] published an anti-suffrage drama in 1896, called ''A Victim of Women's Rights''.{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=306}} Many anti-suffrage dramas were overtly political and incorporated the use of [[farce]] to paint suffragists as "self-absorbed" and "mannish in dress and manner."{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=305}} They also criticized the idea of the [[New Woman]] in general and advocated for women and men to occupy separate spheres of influence.{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=308}}{{Sfn|Dassori|2005|p=314-315}}

''The Remonstrance'', a journal published by the [[Massachusetts Association Opposed to the Further Extension of Suffrage to Women]] (MAOFESW) between 1890 and 1920 was used to promote anti-suffrage ideas and also to react to and refute the claims of suffragists.{{Sfn|Burt|1998|p=71}}[[Image:Anti-suffragist.jpg|thumb|A political cartoon in ''[[Harper's]]'' lampoons the anti-suffrage movement (1907).]]

=== Early backing for the anti-suffrage movement ===
The anti-suffrage movement began in the United States after the [[Massachusetts General Court|Massachusetts State legislature]] introduced a proposal to promote female voting rights.{{Sfn|Aslanian|2013|p=2}} Two hundred women opposed this initiative as they did not want women to gain full citizenship.<ref>Thomas Jabolonsky, “Female Opposition: The Anti Suffrage Campaign” as featured in Votes for Women: The Struggle for Suffrage Revisited, ed. Jean Baker (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2002), 119.</ref> Though nothing became of this proposal, its introduction mobilized the suffrage movement on both sides.

In 1871, a petition to the [[United States Congress]] was published by nineteen women in [[Godey's Lady's Book|Godey's Lady's Book and Magazine]] in opposition to votes for women, the first instance of the mobilization from anti-suffrage women.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Ritter|first=Gretchen|date=1998-06-01|year=|title=Splintered Sisterhood: Gender and Class in the Campaign against Woman Suffrage by Susan E. Marshall|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.2307/2657874/abstract|journal=Political Science Quarterly|language=en|volume=113|issue=2|pages=20|doi=10.2307/2657874|issn=1538-165X|via=}}</ref>

Women turned out at the [[New York Constitution|New York State Constitutional Convention]] in 1894 to protest women's suffrage.{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=15-16}}

=== Emergence of anti-suffrage organizations ===
In 1895, the [[Massachusetts Association Opposed to the Further Extension of Suffrage to Women]] (MAOFESW) was created and is noted to be the first effort of the anti-suffragists to institutionalize their cause.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Benjamin|first=Anne M.|year=1991|title=A History of the Anti-suffrage Movement in the United States from 1895 to 1920: Women against Equality|url=|journal=Lewiston: Edwin Mellen Press|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In [[Des Moines, Iowa]], 35 women formed the Iowa Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage in 1898.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20052966/|title=Foes of Suffrage Organize|last=|first=|date=23 February 1898|work=Daily News-Democrat|access-date=2018-05-13|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[California]], [[Illinois]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Oregon]], [[South Dakota]] and [[Washington (state)|Washington]] all formed groups by 1900.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=287}} [[Ohio]] formed an anti suffrage group, the Ohio Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage in 1902.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/05/09/100534217.pdf|title=Ohio's Silent Womanhood|last=|first=|date=9 May 1912|work=New York Times|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>

The [[New York State Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage]] was founded in 1897, and by 1908 it had over 90 members.<ref>[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.rbc/rbcmil.scrp5011203 ''New York State Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage Thirteenth Annual Report''], 1908</ref> It was active in producing pamphlets and publications explaining their views of women's suffrage, until the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] was passed in 1920. A [[Geneva, New York|Geneva]] branch was founded in 1909.<ref>[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.rbc/rbcmil.scrp5011202 ''Against Suffrage''], newspaper clipping, 1909</ref> The [[suffragists]] in New York often extended invitations to open discussion with the anti-suffragists.<ref>[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.rbc/rbcmil.scrp6005403 ''Mrs. Mackay's Campaign''], newspaper clipping, 25 January 1910</ref> The New York association had its own magazine, ''The Anti-Suffragist'', published by Mrs. William Winslow Crannell from July 1908 to April 1912.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Anti-Suffragist|title=The Anti-Suffragist {{!}} American periodical|newspaper=Encyclopædia Britannica|access-date=2016-12-21}}</ref>

The [[National Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage]] (NAOWS) was the first national organization of women who challenged the fight for women's suffrage.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Righting Feminism: Conservative Women and American Politics|last=Schreiber|first=Ronnee|publisher=Oxford University Press, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=19|quote=|via=}}</ref> Several state associations assembled for an anti-suffrage convention in New York City and formed the NAOWS.{{Sfn|Aslanian|2013|p=2}} The association gained significant momentum between 1912 and 1916<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Susan E.|date=1985-04-01|title=Ladies Against Women: Mobilization Dilemmas of Antifeminist Movements|url=http://socpro.oxfordjournals.org/content/32/4/348|journal=Social Problems|language=en|volume=32|issue=4|pages=348–362|doi=10.2307/800757|issn=0037-7791}}</ref> and was operational in twenty-five states.<ref>Kim Nielsen, Un-American Womanhood: Antiradicalism, Antifeminism, and the First Red Scare, (2001), Introduction.</ref> The NAOWS was said to have as many as 350,000 members.<ref name=":0" /> At the start, the organization was run by [[Josephine Jewell Dodge|Josephine Dodge]] and Minnie Bronson.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=284}} [[Alice Hay Wadsworth]], wife of [[James Wolcott Wadsworth Jr.]], assumed leadership of the association when it moved its headquarters from New York to Washington D.C. in 1917.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=284}} NAOWS produced ''The Woman's Protest'', a newsletter that helped defeat close to forty woman suffrage referenda.<ref name=":1" />

[[Everett P. Wheeler]], a lawyer from New York, created the [[Man-Suffrage Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage]] in 1913.{{Sfn|Goodier|Pastorello|p=110|2017}} This organization was made up of powerful and affluent men and started out with around 600 members opposed to women's suffrage.{{Sfn|Goodier|Pastorello|p=110|2017}}

=== World War I ===
Anti-suffragists helped contribute to war relief work during [[World War I]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.massmoments.org/moment-details/voters-deny-massachusetts-women-the-vote.html|title=Voters Deny Massachusetts Women the Vote|last=|first=|date=|website=Mass Moments|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416154159/https://www.massmoments.org/moment-details/voters-deny-massachusetts-women-the-vote.html|archive-date=16 April 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref>{{Sfn|Goodier|Pastorello|p=6|2017}} NAOWS contributed to the [[Belgium|Belgian]] war relief effort.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20047034/|title=Fund Goes to Belgians|last=|first=|date=15 January 1915|work=The Times Dispatch|access-date=2018-05-13|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Many anti-suffrage groups highlighted their charitable efforts, painting themselves as "self-sacrificing."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=43}} They wanted the country to see that women could make a difference without the vote, however, it was partly the efforts of women aiding the war that helped women gain the vote in the end.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=43-44}}

=== Reasons for suffrage opposition ===
There were several concerns that drove the anti-suffrage argument. Anti-suffragists felt that giving women the right to vote would threaten the family institution.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/03612759.1998.10528202|title=Woman Suffrage and the Origins of Liberal Feminism in the United States, 1820-1920|last=Marilley|first=Suzanne M.|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1996|isbn=|location=Cambridge|pages=4|doi=10.1080/03612759.1998.10528202|quote=|via=Taylor and Francis Online}}</ref> [[Illinois]] anti-suffragist, [[Caroline Corbin]] felt that women's highest duties were motherhood and its responsibilities.{{Sfn|Dodd|2013|p=722}} Some saw women's suffrage as in opposition to God's will.<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|title=The ideas of the woman suffrage movement, 1890-1920.|last=Kraditor|first=Aileen|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1962|isbn=|location=|pages=15|quote=|via=}}</ref> Antis such as [[Catharine Beecher]] and [[Sarah Josepha Hale|Sara Josepha Hale]] both shared a religiously based criticism of suffrage and believed women should be only involved with ''[[Kinder, Küche, Kirche]]'' (children, kitchen and church).{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=49}} Some anti-suffragists didn't want the vote because they felt it violated traditional [[Gender role|gender norms]].{{Sfn|Dodd|2013|p=719}} Many anti-suffragists felt that if women gained the vote there would be an end to "true womanhood."{{Sfn|Dodd|2013|p=723}}

There were also those who thought that women could not handle the responsibility of voting because they lacked knowledge of that beyond the domestic sphere and they feared government would be weakened by introducing this ill-informed electorate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=S. E.|date=1986-12-01|title=In Defense of Separate Spheres: Class and Status Politics in the Antisuffrage Movement|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/sf/65.2.327|journal=Social Forces|volume=65|issue=2|pages=327–351|doi=10.1093/sf/65.2.327|issn=0037-7732}}</ref> Anti-suffragists did not see voting as a "right," but as a "duty" and that women already had their own unique responsibilities and duties in the [[Private sphere|domestic sphere]].{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=288}} Also, since Antis believed that governments had authority due to "force," women wouldn't be able to "enforce the laws they may enact."<ref name=":7">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20164036/|title=Mrs. George to Address Anti-Suffragists Here|last=|first=|date=11 October 1914|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

Anti-suffragists, such as [[Josephine Jewell Dodge|Josephine Dodge]], argued that giving women the right to vote would overburden them and undermine their privileged status.<ref name=":0" /> They saw participation in the private sphere as essential to a woman's role and thought that giving them public duties would prevent them from fulfilling their primary responsibilities in the home. Anti-suffragists claimed that they represented the "silent majority" of America who did not want to enter the public sphere by gaining the right to vote.<ref>Camhi, J. J. (2007). Women Against Women: American Antisuffragism, 1880–1920. ''Understanding Inequality: The Intersection of Race/Ethnicity, Class, and Gender'', 225-239.</ref> Being against women's suffrage didn't mean, however, that all Antis were against civic pursuits.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=40}} [[Jeanette L. Gilder]], a journalist, wrote "Give women everything she wants, but not the ballot. Open every field of learning, every avenue of industry to her, but keep her out of politics."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=40-41}} Dodge encouraged women to become involved in "charitable, philanthropic and educational activities."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=40}} It was also cited that women had made reforms such as raising the [[Ages of consent in the United States|age of consent]] without the vote and that gaining this right was therefore unnecessary and could even be harmful to further reform movements.{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=49}} The thought was that women were able to influence the government because they were seen as politically neutral and [[Nonpartisanism|non-partisan]] and giving them the right to vote would strip them of this unique position.<ref>Thurner, M. (1993). "Better citizens without the ballot": American antisuffrage women and their rationale during the Progressive era. Journal of Women's History, 5(1), 33-60.</ref> In addition, because voting is "only a small part of government," they believed there was no need to vote in order to participate in politics.<ref name=":7" /> This particular line of reasoning, that women should stay out of politics, kept the [[General Federation of Women's Clubs]] (GFWC) from officially endorsing suffrage until 1914.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=41}}

Anti-suffragism was not limited to conservative elements. The [[anarchist]] [[Emma Goldman]] opposed suffragism on the grounds that women were more inclined toward legal enforcement of morality (as in the [[Women's Christian Temperance Union]]), that it was a diversion from more important struggles, and that suffrage would ultimately not make a difference. She also said that activists ought to advocate [[revolution]] rather than seek greater privileges within an inherently unjust system.<ref>[[Emma Goldman]]. "[http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/anarchist_archives/goldman/aando/suffrage.html Woman Suffrage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407134611/http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/anarchist_archives/goldman/aando/suffrage.html|date=April 7, 2007}}". ''Anarchism and Other Essays'', 1911.</ref> Anti-suffragists saw women's efforts to gain the vote to be all surface dressing with a lack of serious intent to change the world for the better.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=42}} Other Antis believed that social reform was better accomplished through [[trade union]]s and non-partisan groups.{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=42}} Progressives criticized suffrage in the [[Utah Territory]] as a cynical [[Mormon]] ploy, resulting in the passage of the [[Edmunds-Tucker Act]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}

The anti-suffrage movement began to change in its position against suffrage in 1917, expanding their scope to include anti-[[Political radicalism|radical]] rhetoric.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=285}} The anti-suffrage movement focused less on the issue of suffrage and began to spread fear of radical ideas and to use "conspiratorial paranoia."{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=291}} Suffragists were accused of subversion of the government and [[treason]].{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=292-293}} They were also accused of being [[Socialism|socialists]], "[[Bolsheviks]]" or "unpatriotic German sympathizers."{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=292-293}} The [[Texas]] branch of the NAOWS accused women's suffrage groups of being linked to "socialism, [[anarchy]] and [[Mormonism]]."<ref name=":42">{{Cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/vbtvw|title=Texas Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage|last=Cottrell|first=Debbie Mauldin|date=15 June 2010|website=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref> Accusations of being associated with unpopular radical movements was named after the second president of NAOWS, Alice Wadsworth, and called "Wadsworthy" attacks.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=293}} In addition to associating suffrage with radicalism, the antis also felt that they were [[Oppression|oppressed]] and had lost much perceived political power by 1917.{{Sfn|Maddux|2004|p=293}}

Anti-suffrage movements in the [[Southern United States|American South]] included an appeal to conservatism and [[white supremacy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womensuffrage.org/?p=570|title=Anti-Suffrage Movements in the USA South|last=LeBaron|first=Genevieve|date=1 February 2012|website=Women Suffrage and Beyond|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428163937/http://womensuffrage.org/?p=570|archive-date=28 April 2017|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-20}}</ref> In [[Virginia]], the NAOWS chapter even linked [[Ethnic conflict|race riots]] to women's suffrage.<ref name=":52">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/7487700/|title=Shall the State Surrender to the Anthony Amendment?|last=|first=|date=|work=The Times Dispatch|access-date=2018-05-13|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

=== Anti-suffragism after the nineteenth amendment ===
Once the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|nineteenth amendment]] was passed, some women who opposed suffrage exercised this right.<ref name=":5">{{Cite journal|last=Goodier|first=Susan|date=2007|title=The Other Woman's Movement: Anti-suffrage Activism in New York State, 1865-1932|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/de3a23f495ced83fc68f14ef4ea719a8/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=18750&diss=y|journal=ProQuest Dissertations Publishing|volume=|pages=|subscription=yes|via=ProQuest}}</ref>{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=145}} They took the energy they were investing in the anti-suffrage movement and turned it towards supporting the platform of the Republican party.{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=147}}{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=148}} Former members of anti-suffrage groups in New York became involved in the [[Women's National Republican Club]].{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=151}} In this way, they left the private sphere and entered the public sphere, one of the things that they were resisting in their anti-suffrage efforts. Former anti-suffragist, [[Ida Tarbell]], pointed out that it would take some time for women to get comfortable with voting.{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=145-146}} Some women didn't vote or get involved in politics.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wa5BgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=How%20Did%20Women%20Antifeminists%20Shape%20and%20Limit%20the%20Social%20Reform%20Movements%20of%20the%201920s&pg=PA190#v=onepage&q=anti-suffrage&f=false|title=Women, Politics and Change|last=Andersen|first=Kristi|publisher=Russell Sage Foundation|year=1990|isbn=9781610445344|editor-last=Tilly|editor-first=Louise A.|location=|pages=190–191|language=en|chapter=Women and Citizenship in the 1920s|editor-last2=Gurin|editor-first2=Patricia}}</ref> Others, like [[Annie Nathan Meyer]] advocated for all anti-suffrage women to not vote in order to allow the country to suffer from what she saw as a terrible decision to allow women to vote.{{Sfn|Goodier|2013|p=144}}

The passage of the Nineteenth Amendment also kickstarted a coalition of anti-suffragists who organized themselves into a political anti-feminist movement in order to "oppose expansion of social welfare programs, women's peace efforts, and to foster a political culture hostile to progressive female activists. This coalition effectively blended anti-feminism and anti-radicalism by embracing and utilizing the hysteria of the post-World War I Red Scare."<ref>Nielsen, Kim. "How Did Women Antifeminists Shape and Limit the Social Reform Movements of the 1920s?". State University of New York at Binghamton, 2004. (electronic resource).</ref>

== Criticism ==
[[File:Anti_Satire_by_Alice_Duer_Miller.jpg|thumb|[[Alice Duer Miller|Alice Duer Miller's]] satire of Anti-Suffrage arguments from ''The Daily Telegram'' in 1916.]]
There was contemporary criticism of the anti-suffrage movement in the United States. One criticism was that anti-suffragists did not present a consistent argument against suffrage.<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20229597/|title=Agitation Against Woman's Suffrage|last=|first=|date=4 February 1900|work=Washington Times|access-date=2018-05-20|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Other arguments were seen as inconsistent, such as Antis claiming that voting meant women must hold office, when members of anti-suffrage groups were already holding offices such as being on the [[Board of education|school board]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20231008/|title=Women and Office Holding|last=|first=|date=28 January 1903|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-05-20|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Other critics, such as [[Alice Stone Blackwell]], pointed out that the anti-suffrage groups exaggerated certain claims, such as membership numbers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20230024/|title=Clipping from - Newspapers.com|last=Miss Blackwell's Statistics|first=|date=|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-05-20|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Critics also argued that there were no new arguments presented over time.<ref name=":8" /> Anti-suffrage groups were also criticized for being "inconsistent" in that they wanted women out of the public sphere, yet they gathered together into public lobbying groups against suffrage.<ref name=":8" /> ''[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review|The Valley Independent]]'' wrote in 1915 that any organization that wanted to oppose women's suffrage and which was made up of women "leaves a bad taste in our mouth."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/20236296/|title=Their Privilege|last=|first=|date=2 February 1915|work=The Valley Independent|access-date=2018-05-20|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

Some critics were "almost contemptuous," such as [[Anna Howard Shaw]], who said, "You'd think they would have loyalty enough to their sex not to make us all out a set of fools."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=33-34}} Shaw believed that Antis were "puppets of more power male forces."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=33-34}} [[Florence Kelley]] called anti-suffragists "lazy, comfortable, sheltered creatures, caring nothing for the miseries of the poor."{{Sfn|Thurner|1993|p=38}}

== Archives ==
The archives of the Women's National Anti-Suffrage League are held at [[The Women's Library]] at the [http://www.lse.ac.uk/library/Home.aspx Library of the London School of Economics], ref [http://twl-calm.library.lse.ac.uk/CalmView/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=Overview.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo='2WNA')  2WNA]

The Library and Archives division of the [[Georgia Historical Society]] have a collection of broadsides from the National Association Opposed to Woman Suffrage from 1917–1919. The documents appear to be printed by state affiliates of the national group. One of the documents was issued by The Men's Anti-Ratification League of Montgomery, Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgiahistory.com/containers/2 |title=Georgia Historical Society |publisher=Georgiahistory.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-13}}</ref>

